, Jan Pedersen (CUMZ-8-57)
</materialsCitation>
. 
<typeStatus box="[326,424,1799,1823]" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Paratype</typeStatus>
male, same data as holotype. Description. Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[1087,1184,1798,1823]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
. Cheek with 5 bristles and jowl with two that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels, without SPS vesicles, palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 106</figureCitation>
. Left face of thorax as 
<figureCitation box="[452,547,1870,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Fig. 107</figureCitation>
, with 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these; and mesopleuron with only 3–4 hairs. Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites light brown with hairs largely restricted to hind margins and those at rear of T6 not longer than those at rear of T5. Venter gray, and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[867,1023,1978,2003]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="77">Figs 108–112</figureCitation>
. Legs light brown to dusky yellow.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617713/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="78" startId="15.[151,264,1953,1976]" targetBox="[265,1320,198,1913]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1953,2006]" pageId="15" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,357,1953,1976]" pageId="15" pageNumber="78">FIGURES 92–102.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Henry &amp; Bøggild, 2019" authorityName="Henry &amp; Bøggild" authorityYear="2019" box="[367,615,1954,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parhirticruss" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[367,615,1954,1976]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="78">Megaselia parhirticruss</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[625,687,1954,1975]" pageId="15" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[625,687,1954,1975]" pageId="15" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
male. 92. head. 93 proboscis from below. 94. left face of thorax. 95. scutellum. 96–98. hypopygium. 99. front tarsus. 100. mid tibia and basitarsus. 101. hind femur. 102. basal half of wing.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption box="[151,1114,704,727]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617715/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" startId="16.[151,264,704,727]" targetBox="[183,1396,219,656]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1114,704,727]" box="[151,1114,704,727]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,365,704,727]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">FIGURES 103–104.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[371,570,705,727]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirticrus">
<emphasis box="[371,570,705,727]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Megaselia hirticrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male. 103. left face of hypopygium. 104. hind femur.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,766,1407]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">
Fore tarsus as 
<figureCitation box="[316,412,766,791]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Fig. 113</figureCitation>
, with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and ratios of segment lengths 2.6–2.7: 1.4: 1.1–1.2: 0.9–1.0: 1. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia (
<figureCitation box="[823,918,802,827]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Fig. 114</figureCitation>
) extends 0.4–0.5 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur (
<figureCitation box="[436,531,838,863]" captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Fig. 115</figureCitation>
) shorter than those of anteroventral row of outer half. Hind tibia with two dozen weakly differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 105–117" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[383,1166,229,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[301,1286,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 105–117. Megaselia pederseni sp. n. male. 105. frons. 106. postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 107. left face of thorax. 108–I12. hypopygium. 113. front tarsus. 114. mid tibia. 115, hind femur. 116, wing. 117, basal half of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617717/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Figs 116–117</figureCitation>
) very pale and only 
<quantity box="[478,612,910,935]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="0.6">0.6–1.4 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.0.35–0.40. Costal ratios 2.7–5.6: 1.4–1.0: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[366,529,947,971]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" unit="mm" value="0.12" valueMax="0.13" valueMin="0.11">0.11–0.13 mm</quantity>
long. No hair at base of vein 3. With 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outer being 
<quantity box="[151,314,983,1007]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" unit="mm" value="0.115" valueMax="0.13" valueMin="0.1">0.10–0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not quite reaching R1. Haltere knob gray to brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,766,1407]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1021,1046]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">Recognition.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[356,364,1018,1047]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">.</emphasis>
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[520,714,1021,1046]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
to Group V it runs to couplet 3, but its hypopygium differs from both species. In the key to the males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[778,929,1058,1083]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 124, where the variation in the colour of the haltere knob means both options need to be considered. Lead 1 proceeds to couplet 127, where the very pale wing of lead 1 conflicts with the description of the left hypandrial lobe. The subsequently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geiri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">M. geiri</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
runs to this couplet but its hypopygium differs, with very short hypandrial lobes in particular. Taking the second lead from couplet 124 one proceeds to couplet 143 where the pale wing fits lead 1 but the hypopygium is clearly different. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" authorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[376,675,1238,1263]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indifferens">
<emphasis box="[376,536,1238,1263]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">M. indifferens</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
also runs to this couplet but its hypopygium is also very different (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,1274,1299]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[271,1255,201,1907]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[225,1277,186,1925]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Megaselia anniduedahlae sp. n. male (Figs 1-10). 1. Frons. 2. Postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 3, proboscis from below. 4, left face of hypopygium. 5. Right face of hypopygium. 6. Front leg. 7. segments 4 and 5 of front tarsus. 8. mid tibia. 9. Hind femur. 10. Wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617695/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[213,227,1275,1299]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" unit="in" value="4.0">4</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[267,433,1274,1299]" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" pagination="49 - 53" refId="ref7338" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2011 b) A new species of Megaselia Rondani (Dipt., Phoridae) from Finland. Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 147, 49 - 53." type="journal article" year="2011">Disney, 2011b</bibRefCitation>
) and its wings are tinged gray with veins 4–7 brown. In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz, H. &amp; Delage, A." pageId="16" pageNumber="79" pagination="638 - 664" refId="ref7643" refString="Schmitz, H. &amp; Delage, A. (1974) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. 4 (33). Lieferung 301. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 638 - 664." type="book chapter" year="1974">Schmitz &amp; Delage (1974)</bibRefCitation>
to Abteilung V it runs to couplets 5 or 6, depending on the haltere knob colour, but the hypopygia of the species clearly differ from that of 
<emphasis box="[532,685,1346,1371]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Bøggild" authorityYear="2019" box="[532,682,1346,1371]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pederseni">M. pederseni</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The very pale wings excludes numerous species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
